# {PROJECT_TITLE} - Memory Maintenance

A light routine that keeps memory accurate without becoming a chore. The point
is continuity, not bookkeeping, so default to the smallest action that keeps the
next session oriented.

## After each working session

1. Run the conductor-memory skill on the session ("build conductor memory").
2. Run `integration.py` to copy the new pack into the vault and refresh the
   Claude Code resume pointer.
3. Skim the new MEMORY_INDEX - if the "resume here" note is wrong, fix that one
   line. That single line does most of the work next session.

## Weekly

1. Open MEMORY_LOG.md and confirm the latest few sessions are listed.
2. Fold any durable new preference or decision into the project-context file so
   it survives even if individual session packs get archived.
3. Delete packs from throwaway/exploratory sessions you will not resume.

## Keeping it lean over time

- Archive packs older than ~30 days into an `archive/` subfolder; keep their
  one-line entries in MEMORY_LOG.md so the trail stays intact.
- When several packs cover the same milestone, write one consolidated summary
  and archive the rest. Fewer, denser memories beat many shallow ones.
- If you wire up a vector/MCP store, let it hold the long tail and keep the
  vault index as the human-readable spine.

## Backups

- The vault is the source of truth; whatever backs up the vault backs up memory.
- Before a big restructure, copy the memory subdir somewhere safe first.
